50|$|Truffle oil is {{frequently}} {{used as a}} bait for truffle-hunting dogs and pigs. Modern Italians often use a strufion, a ball of rags scented <b>with</b> <b>truffle</b> oil. Truffle oil {{has been used for}} this purpose since at least 1756, made by boiling truffles in olive oil and given to hunting dogs.|$|R
50|$|Sottocenere al tartufo is a {{very pale}} yellow to off-white cheese <b>with</b> <b>truffles</b> that has a grey-brown ash rind. It has a {{somewhat}} mild taste and is semi-soft in firmness.|$|R
50|$|It is {{sometimes}} {{claimed that the}} ancient Roman, as well as medieval, cooked <b>stuffed</b> animals <b>with</b> other animals. An anonymous Andalusian cookbook from the 13th century includes a recipe for a ram <b>stuffed</b> <b>with</b> small birds. A similar recipe for a camel <b>stuffed</b> <b>with</b> sheep <b>stuffed</b> <b>with</b> bustards <b>stuffed</b> <b>with</b> carp <b>stuffed</b> <b>with</b> eggs is mentioned in T.C. Boyle's book Water Music.|$|R
